@ewencp 
in KafkaConsumer::poll(long timeout), if the timeout is 0, it will return immediately with any records that are already available;
The code is like below:

``` java
do {
  records=pollOnce(remaining);
  if(!records.isEmpty) {
    fetcher.initFetches(metadata.fetch());  // fetcher init another request to prefetch data for performance 
    client.quickPoll();
    return new ConsumerRecords<>(records);
  }
  long elapsed = time.milliseconds() - start;
  remaining = timeout - elapsed;
} while (remaining>0);
```

Let's take a look at KafkaConfigStorage
the process is like below:

``` java
KafkaConfigStorage::putTaskConfigs(configs) {
  configLog.readToEnd();
  configLog.send()    //send taskConfig;
  configLog.readToEnd();
  configLog.send()   //send taskConfig commit;
  configLog.readToEnd();
```

Is it possible that the consumer fetcher inits another fetch request just after sending taskConfig commit and before KafkaBasedLog::poll(0)?
If so, the poll(0) inside KafkaBasedLog::readToLogEnd() will return data, which will cause the consumedCallback of KafkaConfigStorage called first time;
And then, consumer of KafkaBasedLog seek back to the start position, and start to consume the taskConfig commit message again;
In KafkaConfigStorage::consumedCallback:onCompletion：

``` java
Map<ConnectorTaskId, Map<String, String>> deferred = deferredTaskUpdates.get(connectorName);
int newTaskCount = intValue(((Map<String, Object>) value.value()).get("tasks"));
Map<String, Set<Integer>> updatedConfigIdsByConnector = taskIdsByConnector(deferred);
Set<Integer> taskIdSet = updatedConfigIdsByConnector.get(connectorName);
if (!completeTaskIdSet(taskIdSet, newTaskCount)) {
  inconsistent.add(connectorName);
} else {
  if (deferred != null) {
       taskConfigs.putAll(deferred);
       updatedTasks.addAll(taskConfigs.keySet());
   }
inconsistent.remove(connectorName);
}
if (deferred != null)
  deferred.clear();
```

every time task config commit message received, the callback will try to get connector's defered task updates, process and clear;
If the taskConfig commit message again is consumed twice; at first time, the defered task updates will be processed and cleared, the second time will result in NullPointerException;
If above make sense, I think there needs to be more code to tackle the special case;
